Panic's Limit
Copenhagen – We often hear that the world as we know it will meet its end, usually in terms of ecological collapse.
Actually, since the Club of Rome published its prophetic report "The Limits to Growth" over forty years ago, its basic idea has been accompanying us.
But time is not forgiving.
The 1972 report "The Limits to Growth" warned humans that catastrophic collapse is at our fingertips.
However, after that, we only saw financial panic but no real shortages or production collapse.
On the contrary, human ingenuity created resources that were more than sufficient to meet human consumption.
Nevertheless, the basic idea of "The Limits of Growth" still holds true: we continue a trend, entangled in a misleading solution to minor issues, while neglecting the big problems and wise solutions.
In the early 1970s, the optimism about technology faded, the Vietnam War turned into a disaster, society was plunged into turmoil, and the economy stagnated.
Rachel Carson's "Silent Spring" in 1962 ignited panic over pollution, and sparked the modern environmentalist movement; Paul Ehrlich's "Population Bomb" in 1968 said it all.
On the first Earth Day in 1970, people were pessimistic.
The intention of "The Limits to Growth" is to make people worry about resource depletion.
This is our fate because too many people want to consume too much.
Even if our genius wins us some time, we will ultimately destroy the earth and ourselves with pollution.
The only hope is to achieve social stability on a significantly more poverty-stricken level, by halting economic growth itself, reducing consumption, recycling, and forcing people to have fewer children.
This viewpoint is still resonating today, despite being completely wrong.
For example, the author of "The Limits to Growth" predicted that before 2013, the world would run out of aluminum, copper, gold, lead, mercury, molybdenum, natural gas, oil, silver, tin, tungsten, and zinc.
However, although commodity prices have recently rebounded, they have overall fallen to one-third of their levels 150 years ago.
Technical innovation replaced mercury in batteries, dental materials, and thermometers, and by the year 2000, mercury consumption had fallen by 98% and prices had fallen by 90%.
More broadly, since 1946, copper, aluminum, iron, and zinc supplies have all exceeded demand, thanks to the discovery of new reserves and the development of more economical extraction technologies.
Similarly, oil and natural gas were originally expected to be depleted separately in 1990 and 1992; nowadays, the reserves of both are higher than in 1970, despite our consumption having increased significantly.
Over the past six years, shale gas alone has doubled the potential amount of natural gas resources in the United States, with prices cut by half.
As for economic collapse, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change estimates that global per capita GDP will increase by 14 times this century, with developing countries increasing by 24 times.
The Limits to Growth was wrong because it ignored the greatest of all resources: our own ingenuity.
Population growth has slowed since the 1960s.
Grain supply has not collapsed (15 billion acres of arable land are being used, and there are also 2.7 billion acres in reserve) 。
Nutritional deficiencies have been eliminated by more than half, from 35% of the world's population to 16 % 。
Pollution has not given us a hard time.
The Roman Club imagined in a pastoral past that we had no floating particulate air pollution, all happy farmers, and in the future, chimney smoke would make us unable to breathe. Reality is completely the opposite.
In 1900, the global population was only 1.5 billion, and nearly 3 million people died each year —— about 500 people per 500,000 —— due to air pollution, most of which was indoor air pollution.
Nowadays, this ratio has dropped to one death per 2000 people.
Although the number of deaths due to pollution is still higher than that of malaria, its mortality rate is declining rather than rising.
Despite this, the ideas fostered by "The Limits to Growth" are still influencing the thinking of the general public and the elite.
Take recycling for example, it's usually just a gesture to ease people's conscience, and it costs a lot but has little effect on the environment.
For instance, paper usually comes from sustainable forests, not tropical rainforests.
The programs and government subsidies related to paper recycling brought low-quality paper, but protected resources that are not under threat.
Similarly, policies worried about overpopulation leading to self-destruction, such as China's family planning and India's forced sterilization.
Furthermore, despite the fact that pesticides and other pollutants are believed to kill half of humanity, good pesticide regulation has resulted in only 20 deaths per year in the US, while the use of pesticides has created more affordable and abundant food supplies.
In fact, relying solely on organic agriculture — stimulated by the pesticide panic — would bring an additional $100 billion in extra costs to the US each year.
Agricultural efficiency would be reduced by 16%, and to maintain current output, an additional 65 million hectares of land would have to be farmed — half the area of modern California.
Price increases will lead to a decrease in the consumption of fruits and vegetables, resulting in severe negative health impacts (including tens of thousands of additional cancer deaths each year).
Obsessing over dark scenarios prevents us from paying attention to the real global threats.
Poverty is one of the biggest killers, and yet diseases that are easily curable still cause 15 million deaths each year —— equivalent to one-quarter of all deaths.
The solution lies in economic growth.
Once people are lifted out of poverty, most are able to afford the cost of preventing infectious diseases.
Over the past thirty years, more than 680 million Chinese people have escaped poverty, leading to a nearly one billion reduction in the world's poor population.
This has brought about a significant improvement in health, life expectancy, and living standards.
The forty years of history since the publication of "The Limits to Growth" have shown that we need more, not less, growth.
The expansion of trade is estimated to bring in over 10 trillion dollars per year by the end of this century, with benefits far exceeding the "feverish" policies driven by fear that have been trumpeted in the name of caution.
But this requires abandoning anti-growth thinking and using our boundless potential to create a brighter future.
